Q1) Linear Search: Check if a particular customer account ID exists in the list
#include <stdio.h>
#include <conio.h>
void main()
{
    int accounts[50], n, i, searchID, found = 0;
   clrscr(); // clear screen (Turbo C specific)
 printf("Enter number of customer accounts: ");
 scanf("%d", &n);
printf("Enter %d customer account IDs:\n", n);
  for (i = 0; i < n; i++)
    {
         printf("Account ID %d: ", i + 1);
        scanf("%d", &accounts[i]);
    }
      printf("\nEnter Account ID to search: ");
    scanf("%d", &searchID);
     for (i = 0; i < n; i++)
    {
        if (accounts[i] == searchID)
        {
            found = 1;
            break;
        }
    }
    if (found == 1)
        printf("\nAccount ID %d found at position %d.\n", searchID, i + 1);
    else
        printf("\nAccount ID %d not found in the list.\n", searchID);
      getch(); // wait for key press (Turbo C specific)
}

Algorithm for Linear Search (to check if an account ID exists)

1.Start
2.Read the number of customer accounts → n
3.Create an array to store n account IDs
4.For every index from 0 to n-1:
-Read each account ID and store it in the array
5.Read the account ID you want to search → searchID
6.Set a flag variable found = 0
7.For every index from 0 to n-1:
-If the current element equals searchID
-Set found = 1
-Stop the loop (break)
8.If found is 1:
-Print that the account ID is found
-Print its position
9.Else:
-Print that the account ID is not found
10.Stop
